            <div type="general">
               <p>Jijel is a northeastern Algerian coastal city situated in the region of Corniche Jjilienne. Due to the rugged landscape, it is rather isolated. Although today the majority speak Arabic, Jijel’s population is of Berber descent – mainly of the Kutama tribe. Therefore the dialect of Jijel shows certain influences of a Berber substratum.  </p>
            </div>

            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:QDYKKRHC">Marçais (1945-1948)</rs> is a short article on plural agreement in the 
               Jijel dialect of some usually singular nouns. <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:Y37XX42R">Marçais (1954)</rs> is a 
               collection of texts, including five on everyday life, six folk narratives, and twelve songs in the dialect 
               of Jijel. <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:VN6XFWA6">Marçais (1956)</rs> is a comprehensive study of the dialect of Jijel, 
               including an extraordinarily long section on phonology (140 pages), and chapters (of at least 100 pages each) on the 
               verb, the noun, pronouns, and particles. The chapter on syntax, however, consists of only ten pages focusing on topics 
               like affirmation and negation. In the conclusion, the author discusses the Jijel dialect's Berber substratum and its innovative features.</p>
            </div>

            <div type="dictionaries">
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:Y37XX42R">Marçais (1954)</rs> includes a glossary of about 40 pages. 
               <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:VN6XFWA6">Marçais (1956)</rs> contains significant lexicographical information.</p>
            </div>

